65
00:04:00,140 --> 00:04:04,463
I realized the same principles can be applied fundamentally across types of generators,

66
00:04:04,463 --> 00:04:07,885
whether you're generating civilizations or furniture or people.

67
00:04:08,625 --> 00:04:13,249
If you're curious about text generation in particular, I do recommend checking out Tracery

68
00:04:13,249 --> 00:04:17,212
or Cheap Bots Done Quick, which is what made this lovely Twitter bot.

69
00:04:17,212 --> 00:04:22,316
But for this talk, I will generally be assuming that you're generating actual characters,

70
00:04:22,316 --> 00:04:26,600
full characters as game objects, not just text generation.

71
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:32,485
So that any time I refer to generating text, I'm probably using it as a symbol for a greater

72
00:04:32,485 --> 00:04:34,006
data space, if that makes sense.

73
00:04:34,456 --> 00:04:38,457
But I'm focusing on characters in this talk because they are a common fantasy for procedural

74
00:04:38,457 --> 00:04:42,018
designers and a common nightmare for writers.

75
00:04:42,018 --> 00:04:45,658
And they're a fantasy slash nightmare for the exact same reasons, which is that humans

76
00:04:45,658 --> 00:04:50,860
are excellent pattern finders and patterns in generated people feel more artificial and

77
00:04:50,860 --> 00:04:54,240
alienating than patterns that we see in generated places or objects.

78
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:59,341
There is no such thing as an uncanny valley for furniture, right?

79
00:04:59,341 --> 00:05:02,662
So if we can generate people, we can generate anything.

80
00:05:03,808 --> 00:05:06,850
So ideally we want characters' diverse information bits

81
00:05:06,850 --> 00:05:08,751
to funnel down into a singular,

82
00:05:08,751 --> 00:05:10,952
perfect moment of understanding.

83
00:05:10,952 --> 00:05:12,653
And so we need to change the way that we write

84
00:05:12,653 --> 00:05:13,833
and the way that our writing is used

85
00:05:13,833 --> 00:05:17,616
so that a bunch of words can become meaningful,

86
00:05:17,616 --> 00:05:19,316
memorable moments for our players.

87
00:05:20,663 --> 00:05:22,564
So, I'm gonna break this down into four things.

88
00:05:22,564 --> 00:05:26,747
Overall, the base fundamentals are building orthogonally,

89
00:05:26,747 --> 00:05:28,109
and then we're gonna talk a little bit

90
00:05:28,109 --> 00:05:30,750
about creating higher order meaning,

91
00:05:30,750 --> 00:05:32,712
and then we're going to talk about surfacing that meaning

92
00:05:32,712 --> 00:05:36,275
to the player, and then why iteration with your co-authors

93
00:05:36,275 --> 00:05:39,397
is actually extra important in this particular field.

94
00:05:39,397 --> 00:05:41,719
So, orthogonality I'm gonna use a lot.

95
00:05:41,719 --> 00:05:44,961
I didn't have a lazy colloquialism for this one.

96
00:05:44,961 --> 00:05:46,723
And I'm gonna use it because...

97
00:05:47,383 --> 00:05:51,088
Well, to clarify what I mean by system-driven, I don't mean linear and I also don't mean

98
00:05:51,088 --> 00:05:51,528
branching.

99
00:05:51,528 --> 00:05:52,650
That's kind of barely a system.

100
00:05:52,650 --> 00:05:57,015
What I'm talking about is system-driven games that provide a possibility space for the player

101
00:05:57,015 --> 00:05:58,176
to explore.

102
00:05:58,176 --> 00:06:03,163
So rather than telling a particular story or a particular set of stories, we're instead

103
00:06:03,163 --> 00:06:05,766
only saying these are the kinds of things...

104
00:06:06,106 --> 00:06:09,528
the kinds of stories that might be told in my game.

105
00:06:09,528 --> 00:06:11,709
And those boundaries are here marked

106
00:06:11,709 --> 00:06:14,210
on this helpful diagram as X1, X2, and X3.

107
00:06:14,210 --> 00:06:17,271
And that was coined as a story volume

108
00:06:17,271 --> 00:06:19,172
at Project Horseshoe a couple years ago.

109
00:06:19,172 --> 00:06:20,493
And in Jason Grinblatt's words,

110
00:06:20,493 --> 00:06:21,913
a story volume quote,

111
00:06:21,913 --> 00:06:24,735
encloses a family of emergent stories

112
00:06:24,735 --> 00:06:27,476
created by a set of carefully curated system parameters.

113
00:06:27,976 --> 00:06:29,999
And these parameters are often fluffy,

114
00:06:29,999 --> 00:06:32,783
things like themes and your setting and so on.

115
00:06:32,783 --> 00:06:36,107
Maybe your story volume includes societal collapse

116
00:06:36,107 --> 00:06:38,330
or love ballads or moon festivals.

117
00:06:38,330 --> 00:06:40,973
It's kind of up to you what your story volume is about,

118
00:06:40,973 --> 00:06:43,777
but you are defining what is allowed and what isn't

119
00:06:43,777 --> 00:06:45,399
rather than what should be.

120
00:06:47,502 --> 00:06:52,947
And the key for me was to wrap my head around the orthogonality that in order for this beautiful

121
00:06:52,947 --> 00:06:57,731
space to exist, x1 must be a completely different axis than x2 or x3.

122
00:06:57,731 --> 00:07:03,456
A value on x1 needs to be easily separated from a value on x2 so that they can be combined

123
00:07:03,456 --> 00:07:05,278
to create meaningfully different results.

124
00:07:06,773 --> 00:07:08,834
We're used to thinking of this physically.

125
00:07:08,834 --> 00:07:11,296
We're used to seeing different character traits physically,

126
00:07:11,296 --> 00:07:14,579
such as height or weight, be combined freely.

127
00:07:14,579 --> 00:07:19,523
To use an example from Emily Short's chapter 21 in my book,

128
00:07:19,523 --> 00:07:21,224
height and weight can be considered orthogonal,

129
00:07:21,224 --> 00:07:22,485
and usually are.

130
00:07:22,485 --> 00:07:23,326
You can combine them freely.

131
00:07:23,326 --> 00:07:26,248
You could have tall and thin, or tall and wide, whatever.

132
00:07:26,949 --> 00:07:34,993
And you know usually we don't get the impulse to correlate these with each other. We don't suddenly think oh hair length should probably predict a skin color

133
00:07:34,993 --> 00:07:39,576
But we do tend to do that with personalities, and it becomes very fuzzy very quickly

134
00:07:39,576 --> 00:07:45,479
So this might seem up front like an example of four orthogonal personality traits

135
00:07:45,479 --> 00:07:49,442
Combining these let's say you could have you know low or high of any of these four traits

136
00:07:49,842 --> 00:07:52,303
Oh, wow, I can create 60 different personality types.

137
00:07:52,303 --> 00:07:53,604
Incredible.

138
00:07:53,604 --> 00:07:58,447
Unfortunately, as Emily Short points out, this difference might not be observable or

139
00:07:58,447 --> 00:07:59,688
meaningful to the player.

140
00:07:59,688 --> 00:08:04,792
These traits, flirtiness and extroversion in particular, do overlap in the kinds of

141
00:08:04,792 --> 00:08:09,415
behaviors they can create, because both traits govern whether or not a character might want

142
00:08:09,415 --> 00:08:12,797
to talk to you, and if so, how often, how intimately.

143
00:08:13,397 --> 00:08:17,659
So, players won't always see the difference between a very flirty character versus a very

144
00:08:17,659 --> 00:08:18,500
extroverted character.

145
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:22,101
This is also a problem in real life, but that's a different question.

146
00:08:22,101 --> 00:08:26,363
So she recommends, for example, thinking of what if romantic interest replaced flirtiness.

147
00:08:26,363 --> 00:08:30,065
And that's interesting because it is observed under different circumstances.

148
00:08:30,065 --> 00:08:35,227
A shy person can still express high or low romantic interest in the player, and a highly

149
00:08:35,227 --> 00:08:38,308
extroverted can express both of these feelings.

150
00:08:38,308 --> 00:08:40,209
And so they are much more modular.

151
00:08:41,810 --> 00:08:43,050
And after you've picked your orthogonal traits,

152
00:08:43,050 --> 00:08:45,231
this is where it starts getting very tempting

153
00:08:45,231 --> 00:08:47,973
to correlate them, especially in a straightforward,

154
00:08:47,973 --> 00:08:49,813
logical-seeming way.

155
00:08:49,813 --> 00:08:51,694
And you should resist this temptation.

156
00:08:51,694 --> 00:08:54,616
I mean, you might be tempted to make someone imaginative,

157
00:08:54,616 --> 00:08:56,656
much more likely to fall in love with the player,

158
00:08:56,656 --> 00:08:58,737
because that makes sense, right?

159
00:08:58,737 --> 00:09:01,179
Or maybe it's more interesting, or it's more realistic,

160
00:09:01,179 --> 00:09:04,060
or you're afraid of your characters being too random.

161
00:09:04,060 --> 00:09:06,281
But it's bad, and you should think about

162
00:09:06,281 --> 00:09:08,202
orthogonality very deeply, because...

163
00:09:09,402 --> 00:09:14,969
Even if you're talking about orcs, you want orthogonal traits not only for story volume reasons,

164
00:09:14,969 --> 00:09:19,294
but also it allows for the possibility of interesting transformations.

165
00:09:19,294 --> 00:09:23,078
Part of the success of the Nemesis system is that depending on the input,

166
00:09:23,078 --> 00:09:25,821
different traits can be applied and combined at will.

167
00:09:26,362 --> 00:09:31,567
Zun here could be burned or scarred or strengthened in any number of system driven ways depending

168
00:09:31,567 --> 00:09:32,147
on what happens.

169
00:09:32,147 --> 00:09:35,511
He could change completely depending on the player and roll of the dice.

170
00:09:35,511 --> 00:09:41,877
If archers or marksmen here were more likely to get, I don't know, a hand injury, I mean

171
00:09:41,877 --> 00:09:45,941
it would make more sense, but it would also be much less interesting and rich for the

172
00:09:45,941 --> 00:09:46,661
player to explore.

173
00:09:47,773 --> 00:09:53,216
Orthogonal traits also allow you to hide some of those traits and reveal them over time,

174
00:09:53,216 --> 00:09:55,638
letting the player get to know the character in an interesting way.

175
00:09:55,638 --> 00:10:02,202
If being an ascetic, like Zayna there, number four, if being an ascetic implied something

176
00:10:02,202 --> 00:10:05,965
about what kind of vice she had, it wouldn't be interesting to learn what it actually was

177
00:10:05,965 --> 00:10:08,186
because you'd have a feeling of what it was already.

178
00:10:08,186 --> 00:10:12,949
Getting to know her would feel less like meeting someone and more like just filling out the

179
00:10:12,949 --> 00:10:13,870
rest of the cookie cutter.

180
00:10:15,165 --> 00:10:18,350
In Moon Hunters, we made the player myth a bit orthogonal,

181
00:10:18,350 --> 00:10:19,611
such that different components,

182
00:10:19,611 --> 00:10:21,073
such as events that you encountered,

183
00:10:21,073 --> 00:10:23,416
or cause of death, or your constellation,

184
00:10:23,416 --> 00:10:26,641
could be combined at will, which did reduce redundancy,

185
00:10:26,641 --> 00:10:29,484
but the individual pieces remained

186
00:10:29,484 --> 00:10:31,607
maybe too orthogonal, I would say.

187
00:10:32,057 --> 00:10:35,740
I mean, system designers and writers should absolutely work together to keep your story

188
00:10:35,740 --> 00:10:40,183
volume free of arbitrary or logical limitations.

189
00:10:40,183 --> 00:10:45,847
Lateral, meaningful connections between systems can make your story volume absolutely richer,

190
00:10:45,847 --> 00:10:47,228
which we'll talk about in just a moment.

191
00:10:47,228 --> 00:10:52,072
But direct constraints within a single system, such as your character traits, usually make

192
00:10:52,072 --> 00:10:53,093
your story volume poorer.

193
00:10:54,994 --> 00:10:57,595
So let's think with our writer brain.

194
00:10:57,595 --> 00:11:01,117
So how many people here identify primarily as writers?

195
00:11:01,117 --> 00:11:02,098
Writers.

196
00:11:02,098 --> 00:11:03,299
Oh, interesting, interesting.

197
00:11:03,299 --> 00:11:07,922
How many people identify primarily as system designers?

198
00:11:07,922 --> 00:11:10,183
And what about narrative designers?

199
00:11:10,992 --> 00:11:12,733
Okay, okay, interesting, interesting.

200
00:11:12,733 --> 00:11:15,054
Well, I think it is important for system designers

201
00:11:15,054 --> 00:11:16,515
to put on their writer brains also,

202
00:11:16,515 --> 00:11:18,576
but let's all do that,

203
00:11:18,576 --> 00:11:21,458
and think beyond piles of words and descriptors

204
00:11:21,458 --> 00:11:24,860
to figure out what our meaning actually is.

205
00:11:24,860 --> 00:11:25,701
I mean, without a writer,

206
00:11:25,701 --> 00:11:28,902
a person is a meaningful, meaningless jumble of descriptors

207
00:11:28,902 --> 00:11:31,684
and making them feel powerful and coherent

208
00:11:31,684 --> 00:11:35,146
is more than just pruning their vocabulary.

209
00:11:35,146 --> 00:11:38,448
If you do carefully make a pool of possible words,

210
00:11:38,448 --> 00:11:40,049
you do get occasionally interesting outputs.

211
00:11:40,929 --> 00:11:47,076
If you only generate words and actions related to spaceships and aliens, it will feel sci-fi.

212
00:11:47,076 --> 00:11:50,199
And it'll occasionally be kind of sensible and interesting.

213
00:11:50,199 --> 00:11:54,584
But it'll also start feeling like oatmeal eventually, no matter how well you tune it,

214
00:11:54,584 --> 00:11:59,649
because there will be occasional blips of meaning, and the rest won't really fit together.

215
00:11:59,649 --> 00:12:00,390
They'll just be bits.

216
00:12:01,664 --> 00:12:03,526
And it's because you've used the same structure

217
00:12:03,526 --> 00:12:04,487
for all of them.

218
00:12:04,487 --> 00:12:06,890
You've only generated the bottom most layer of meaning,

219
00:12:06,890 --> 00:12:09,033
the corpus of information.

220
00:12:09,033 --> 00:12:11,136
So even if you have an enormous variety of options

221
00:12:11,136 --> 00:12:12,057
in that bottom layer,

222
00:12:12,057 --> 00:12:14,380
players will still be able to sense deeply

223
00:12:14,380 --> 00:12:16,343
that they're all just buckets

224
00:12:16,343 --> 00:12:18,145
filled with different flavors of water.

225
00:12:19,754 --> 00:12:24,178
Artists and writers often create coherence in our creations kind of subconsciously.

226
00:12:24,178 --> 00:12:27,441
We attach meaning and texture to the things we create.

227
00:12:27,441 --> 00:12:31,485
And in this slide, you can kind of see one character that feels aloof, and one that feels

228
00:12:31,485 --> 00:12:34,127
a bit rebellious, and one that might be a bit wistful.

229
00:12:34,127 --> 00:12:38,431
This is conveyed consistently in the design of their posture, their costume, and body.

230
00:12:38,431 --> 00:12:40,173
And yet, they are not cookie cutters.

231
00:12:40,873 --> 00:12:43,274
So you have to help your algorithm do the same thing,

232
00:12:43,274 --> 00:12:46,596
help it make connections between seemingly unconnected systems

233
00:12:46,596 --> 00:12:47,936
and content.

234
00:12:47,936 --> 00:12:49,377
I'm going to talk about how to do that in a moment.

235
00:12:49,377 --> 00:12:52,438
But if you can figure out a way to create higher order

236
00:12:52,438 --> 00:12:54,638
patterns of meaning, even a little bit,

237
00:12:54,638 --> 00:12:55,919
you'll have more satisfying results

238
00:12:55,919 --> 00:12:58,600
because you're varying the shape of the bucket, not just

