And if the player sticks around

490
00:24:27,929 --> 00:24:29,249
to actually observe what's going on,

491
00:24:29,249 --> 00:24:31,729
maybe now we see his name and we're reminded

492
00:24:31,729 --> 00:24:34,490
and we get to see his current status.

493
00:24:34,490 --> 00:24:36,250
We spend a little bit of time with him

494
00:24:36,250 --> 00:24:37,390
to see what's going on.

495
00:24:37,390 --> 00:24:40,171
This is information that might change at any moment.

496
00:24:40,171 --> 00:24:42,691
So, I mean, the player just kind of naturally will assume

497
00:24:42,691 --> 00:24:44,532
that it's not worth paying too much attention to,

498
00:24:44,532 --> 00:24:45,352
but it might be relevant

499
00:24:45,352 --> 00:24:46,492
depending on your gameplay situation.

500
00:24:47,533 --> 00:24:50,198
And finally, if the player opts in,

501
00:24:50,198 --> 00:24:52,401
then they can interact with the character for more detail,

502
00:24:52,401 --> 00:24:54,184
which are the finer details that make him feel

503
00:24:54,184 --> 00:24:55,987
like a real character that the player

504
00:24:55,987 --> 00:24:57,430
can choose to interact with or not.

505
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:02,603
Now this does handily indicate the amount of words we can generally afford to spend

506
00:25:02,603 --> 00:25:07,367
per message, going from fewest on the left to most on the right.

507
00:25:07,367 --> 00:25:11,330
It also lets us prioritize where to spend most of our time writing variety, since obviously

508
00:25:11,330 --> 00:25:14,092
the information on the left side will be seen more frequently.

509
00:25:14,092 --> 00:25:15,833
It does make sense to budget extra variety there.

510
00:25:15,833 --> 00:25:21,297
For example, if you were to write a bunch of greetings for a character, maybe make it

511
00:25:21,297 --> 00:25:23,239
mostly about the changes in notifications.

512
00:25:23,239 --> 00:25:25,040
Maybe that's what greetings should be about.

513
00:25:26,928 --> 00:25:29,809
So now you have an idea of what meaning to give

514
00:25:29,809 --> 00:25:32,671
to your player as quickly as possible.

515
00:25:32,671 --> 00:25:35,513
And I know iteration is probably an overused word

516
00:25:35,513 --> 00:25:38,975
in our industry, it can make a lot of us shudder,

517
00:25:38,975 --> 00:25:41,136
but I think it's worth calling out here specifically

518
00:25:41,136 --> 00:25:43,417
because we're not used to iterating systems

519
00:25:43,417 --> 00:25:46,179
in the same way that we iterate our content.

520
00:25:46,179 --> 00:25:48,520
We usually think that writing procedural content

521
00:25:48,520 --> 00:25:52,062
goes like this, you dream of an infinite possibilities.

522
00:25:52,990 --> 00:25:57,436
You sit down and you think of some actual possible outcomes for your system.

523
00:25:57,436 --> 00:26:00,320
You tell the computer what to do with it and then, yay, we have something beautiful and

524
00:26:00,320 --> 00:26:01,841
unique.

525
00:26:01,841 --> 00:26:05,566
Unfortunately, programmers generally will want to call this moment alpha.

526
00:26:06,679 --> 00:26:07,179
It is not.

527
00:26:07,179 --> 00:26:11,202
Because you really do have to do a few more iterations.

528
00:26:11,202 --> 00:26:14,665
I would call both of these your co-authors.

529
00:26:14,665 --> 00:26:18,107
Your corpus of data and the systems that combine them.

530
00:26:18,107 --> 00:26:20,268
You're both working with them, and they both have their own

531
00:26:20,268 --> 00:26:22,710
flavors and textures they're going to give you.

532
00:26:22,710 --> 00:26:23,571
So now that we know it's not alpha.

533
00:26:24,211 --> 00:26:27,695
You really should take a moment to examine your co-authors and iterate as much as possible

534
00:26:27,695 --> 00:26:31,859
because it's not just your algorithm that adds flavor, it's also what information you're

535
00:26:31,859 --> 00:26:32,699
putting in.

536
00:26:32,699 --> 00:26:37,244
And this might mean your co-members of your writing team or it might mean external public

537
00:26:37,244 --> 00:26:38,765
domain co-authors.

